{"parentUuid":"ae92c95e-e2b2-4389-8999-a07670bafa47","isSidechain":false,"promptId":"2e3b56a1-362d-4490-8fb9-6aae35711adf","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01S36kDkfH8Re9L9CVtY4vLS","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: What Happened\n3\tdescription: >\n4\t  Explain why code looks the way it does by tracing the latest change for a file\n5\t  range or pasted snippet through `git blame` and deduplicated `entire explain`\n6\t  lookups. Use when the user asks what happened, says \"tell me why\" about a code\n7\t  block, is confused about a section of code, asks \"wtf is going on\", \"why is\n8\t  this like this\", \"why was this changed\", or wants provenance for a specific\n9\t  file block.\n10\t---\n11\t\n12\t# What Happened\n13\t\n14\tUse this skill when the user wants a provenance-focused explanation for a code block.\n15\t\n16\t## Response Format\n17\t\n18\tBegin the first successful resolved-code response to this skill invocation with the line:\n19\t\n20\t`Entire What Happened:`\n21\t\n22\tfollowed by a blank line, then the content.\n23\t\n24\t- Apply the header to the **first successful resolved-code response of the invocation only.**\n25\t  If an earlier unresolved-input response omitted the header and the user later disambiguates\n26\t  the target, include the header on the resolved-code response. Do not re-print it on later\n27\t  follow-up turns within the same invocation.\n28\t- Do **not** include the header on unresolved-input responses (e.g. snippet not found,\n29\t  ambiguous snippet, invalid path or range). If the target code was resolved but no\n30\t  checkpoint-backed context exists, still use the header and clearly label the answer as\n31\t  current-code fallback analysis rather than a checkpoint summary.\n32\t- After the header, include exactly one short, original, non-lyrical \"Tell me why\" line\n33\t  randomly chosen from the examples below. Do not quote, paraphrase, or imitate Backstreet\n34\t  Boys lyrics or any other song lyrics.\n35\t\n36\tAllowed examples:\n37\t\n38\t- `Tell me why: the blame points here.`\n39\t- `Tell me why: the diff left a trail.`\n40\t- `Tell me why: the context starts here.`\n41\t\n42\tSupported inputs:\n43\t\n44\t- `path:line`\n45\t- `path:start-end`\n46\t- `path` plus a pasted code snippet from that file\n47\t\n48\tIf the user asks a vague provenance question without a file path, line range, or pasted\n49\tsnippet, ask for the target code and stop without running commands or using the header.\n50\t\n51\t## Goal\n52\t\n53\tFind the most recent change blocks matching the user's target lines, list the matching\n54\tcommit hashes and checkpoint state, then summarize why each block was changed using the\n55\tbest available context. When checkpoint-backed context is unavailable, still\n56\texplain what the current code does as an explicit fallback and clearly mark that explanation\n57\tas not checkpoint-backed.\n58\t\n59\t## Rules\n60\t\n61\t1. Do not guess about file contents or line numbers. Resolve the exact target lines\n62\t   before explaining anything.\n63\t2. Use the installed `entire` binary from `PATH`, not `./entire` from the current repo.\n64\t3. Prefer `git blame` for provenance and `entire explain --commit` for transcript-backed context.\n65\t   Do not use experimental `entire why` for this skill.\n66\t4. Use this skill for latest-change provenance on a specific block. For broad original intent\n67\t   of a symbol, file, or feature, prefer the `explain` skill.\n68\t5. Do not manually hunt through `.git/entire-sessions/` or raw transcript files for commit\n69\t   provenance. If `entire explain` cannot provide transcript context, report the exact\n70\t   missing or unavailable state.\n71\t6. If the user provides a snippet, resolve it to exact line numbers before explaining anything.\n72\t7. If multiple blame blocks match, include all distinct ranges. Deduplicate commit hashes\n73\t   before running `entire explain`; run transcript lookups once per unique commit, not once\n74\t   per range. Also deduplicate checkpoint IDs before expanding checkpoint transcripts; run\n75\t   checkpoint expansion once per unique checkpoint, not once per commit or range.\n76\t8. Distinguish these states explicitly:\n77\t   - no checkpoint is referenced for the commit\n78\t   - a checkpoint is referenced but is unavailable locally or remotely\n79\t   - a checkpoint is available, but full transcript expansion failed and raw transcript\n80\t     expansion was not explicitly requested\n81\t   - the code is untracked, uncommitted, or otherwise has no committed history\n82\t9. For every resolved code block, include either checkpoint-backed history or a fallback\n83\t   explanation of what the current code does. Label fallback explanations as \"not\n84\t   checkpoint-backed\" and do not imply intent or historical rationale from checkpoints.\n85\t10. Treat `entire explain` command output as intermediate source material for summarization.\n86\t   Do not paste raw command output or full transcripts into the user response unless the user\n87\t   explicitly asks for raw output. Include only short error excerpts when they help the user fix\n88\t   a failed lookup.\n89\t11. Keep the final explanation concise and block-focused. Do not summarize unrelated parts\n90\t   of the file.\n91\t\n92\t## Workflow\n93\t\n94\t### 1. Resolve the target block\n95\t\n96\tIf the user did not provide a file path plus exact line/range or pasted snippet, ask them for\n97\tthe target code and stop. Do not run commands or use the `Entire What Happened:` header.\n98\t\n99\tIf the user gave `path:line` or `path:start-end`, use that line or range directly and read\n100\tonly that target from the file before explaining it. If the path does not exist, the file\n101\tcannot be read, or the line/range is outside the file, say so plainly and stop without using\n102\tthe `Entire What Happened:` header.\n103\t\n104\tIf the user gave a path and a snippet:\n105\t\n106\t- Pick the most distinctive exact line from the snippet and search the file with fixed-string\n107\t  matching to find candidate locations:\n108\t\n109\t```bash\n110\tgrep -n -F -- \"<distinctive snippet line>\" \"<path>\"\n111\t```\n112\t\n113\t- Read the small candidate windows around each hit, not the whole file unless the file is\n114\t  already small or the search produces too many candidates to inspect efficiently.\n115\t- Find the exact snippet in the candidate window.\n116\t- Convert the match to `start-end` line numbers.\n117\t- If whitespace differs but the code is otherwise identical, normalize leading indentation and\n118\t  trailing whitespace before deciding the snippet does not match.\n119\t- If the snippet appears multiple times, report the ambiguity and list the candidate ranges\n120\t  instead of picking one silently. Do not use the `Entire What Happened:` header for this\n121\t  unresolved-input response.\n122\t- If the snippet cannot be found exactly, say so plainly and stop rather than inferring a nearby\n123\t  match. Do not use the `Entire What Happened:` header for this unresolved-input response.\n124\t\n125\t### 2. Gather provenance\n126\t\n127\tOnly run blame after the target has been resolved to actual line numbers in the current file.\n128\tDo not run `git blame -L` against an unresolved pasted snippet, inferred nearby block, symbol\n129\tname, or approximate range.\n130\t\n131\tRun:\n132\t\n133\t```bash\n134\tgit blame --porcelain -L <start>,<end> -- \"<path>\"\n135\t```\n136\t\n137\tIf the command fails because the file is untracked, mark the whole target range as an untracked\n138\tfile with no committed history, keep the exact snippet for that range, and continue to fallback\n139\tcode behavior analysis.\n140\t\n141\tIf blame reports an uncommitted pseudo-commit such as all zeroes or `Not Committed Yet`, mark\n142\tthose ranges as local uncommitted changes and do not run `entire explain` for them. If other\n143\ttarget ranges resolve to real commits, continue with those committed ranges.\n144\t\n145\tUse the output to identify every blame block inside the target range. Group adjacent\n146\ttarget lines that resolve to the same commit when they form one contiguous matched block.\n147\tFor each matching block, collect:\n148\t\n149\t- line range\n150\t- matched code snippet from the current file for that exact range\n151\t- commit hash\n152\t- author/summary when helpful for provenance or fallback context\n153\t\n154\tCollect the unique real commit SHAs across all matching blocks while preserving each distinct\n155\trange. Exclude untracked and local uncommitted pseudo-commits from this set. Build a map from\n156\tcommit SHA to all target ranges blamed to that commit. Do not run `entire explain` separately\n157\tfor multiple ranges that share the same commit.\n158\t\n159\tIf the resolved target spans more than 5 unique real commits, stop before running `entire\n160\texplain`. Report the matched ranges and ask the user to narrow the range or confirm the deeper\n161\tlookup. Do not use the `Entire What Happened:` header for this confirmation response.\n162\t\n163\tKeep the exact snippets from the target-resolution read so the final answer can show users\n164\twhich code each provenance entry refers to. Only reread a matched block if the snippet for\n165\tthat range was not already captured.\n166\t\n167\t### 3. Explain each unique commit\n168\t\n169\tFor each unique commit SHA in that map, run exactly once:\n170\t\n171\t```bash\n172\tentire explain --commit <commit-sha> --no-pager\n173\t```\n174\t\n175\tWhen there are multiple unique commits, run those independent commit lookups in parallel when\n176\tthe agent environment supports parallel tool calls.\n177\t\n178\tUse this output to answer the question and identify the checkpoint state. Do not use\n179\t`--search-all` unless the user explicitly asks to widen a failed lookup; it removes branch/depth\n180\tlimits and may be slow.\n181\