annot load it, keep the\n220\tcheckpoint ID in the answer and say \"checkpoint <id> was referenced, but the checkpoint was\n221\tnot available locally or remotely.\" Include the command error only if it helps the user fix\n222\tthe issue, such as authentication or missing remote configuration.\n223\t\n224\tIf the checkpoint loads but `--full` fails, say that checkpoint metadata was available but\n225\tfull transcript expansion failed. If raw transcript detail was not explicitly requested, say\n226\tit was not expanded automatically. Answer checkpoint-backed facts from the `entire\n227\texplain --commit` output, and use current-code fallback analysis for anything that output\n228\tcannot support.\n229\t\n230\tMap each unique commit explanation back to every target range blamed to that commit.\n231\t\n232\t### 4. Add fallback code behavior analysis when needed\n233\t\n234\tFor any resolved range without a checkpoint-backed explanation, still answer what the current\n235\tcode does. This applies when:\n236\t\n237\t- the file is untracked\n238\t- the range is locally uncommitted\n239\t- no checkpoint is referenced for the commit\n240\t- the checkpoint is referenced but unavailable\n241\t- transcript lookup or expansion fails\n242\t- any other provenance command fails after the target code was resolved\n243\t\n244\tUse only source-backed analysis:\n245\t\n246\t- Read the target block and the smallest necessary surrounding scope, such as the enclosing\n247\t  function, type, imports, or constants.\n248\t- Use `grep -n -F` to inspect direct call sites or definitions only when the block cannot be\n249\t  understood from local context.\n250\t- Explain observable behavior, inputs, outputs, side effects, and important branches.\n251\t- Do not present this as historical intent, checkpoint rationale, or an agent transcript summary.\n252\t- State what cannot be known from current code alone.\n253\t\n254\t## Response format\n255\t\n256\tStart with a short provenance summary:\n257\